28 schools have been broken into in KwaZulu-Natal - and that's just since March this year. Education authorities say criminals targeting schools is on the rise in the province, particularly during this Covid-19 lockdown. Courtesy #DStv403 DURBAN - Since March this year, KwaZulu-Natal has seen a large number of school robberies and authorities say criminals are taking advantage of the national lockdown. READ: Decision on school holidays due soon: DBE 28 schools have been broken into in KwaZulu-Natal.The state-of-the-art, multimillion-rand eThekwini Primary School in KwaMashu is the latest to be burgled. All its ICT equipment has been stolen. Another school in Bergville was set alight not so long ago shocking many people in the province. Unions are equally concerned about the impact on pupils. KZN Sadtu secretary Nomarashiya Caluza said, “If you temper with teaching and learning through stealing the resources that are meant to assist our learners and teachers, it means that you are destroying the very same future of our learners that as teachers we try to mold and build.” READ: Teachers employed by SGBs could receive no salaries The provincial school governing body believes the solution lies with the communities to protect school properties. Education authorities and sector stakeholders are calling on the police and the justice system to be harsh with those vandalising, torching and looting schools. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.